{"type":"message","id":"d64fbe59","parentId":"b03771ec","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:46:33.171Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_rtxx3iam05wx_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"#!/bin/zsh\nset -euo pipefail\n\nexport CHROME_BIN=\"${CHROME_BIN:-/Applications/Microsoft Edge.app/Contents/MacOS/Microsoft Edge}\"\n\npython3 - <<'PY'\nimport os,sys,time\nfrom pathlib import Path\nS='/Users/ling/.agent-reach/tools/xiaohongshu-skills/scripts'\nsys.path.insert(0,S)\nfrom chrome_launcher import ensure_chrome\nfrom xhs.cdp import Browser\n\nensure_chrome(port=9222, headless=False)\nb=Browser(host='127.0.0.1', port=9222)\np=b.new_page()\np.navigate('https://www.xiaohongshu.com/explore')\np.wait_for_load(); p.wait_dom_stable(); time.sleep(2)\n\np._send_session('Network.enable', {})\nres = p._send_session('Network.getCookies', {'urls':['https://www.xiaohongshu.com','https://edith.xiaohongshu.com']})\ncookies = res.get('cookies', [])\nweb_session = ''\nfor c in cookies:\n    if c.get('name') == 'web_session' and '.xiaohongshu.com' in (c.get('domain') or ''):\n        web_session = c.get('value', '')\n        break\n\nif not web_session:\n    raise SystemExit('未提取到 web_session（请先登录小红书）')\n\nout = Path('/Users/ling/.openclaw/skills/xiaohongshutools/.env.local')\nout.write_text(f\"WEB_SESSION={web_session}\\nXHS_PROXY=\\n\", encoding='utf-8')\nprint(f'已更新: {out} (len={len(web_session)})')\nPY\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773971193164}}
{"type":"message","id":"7137c838","parentId":"d64fbe59","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:46:54.360Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the problem. The `update_xhs_web_session.sh` script:\n\n1. Launches Chrome at port 9222\n2. Navigates to xiaohongshu.com/explore\n3. Tries to get cookies\n\nThe issue is in the `_connect` function in `cli.py`. When the script runs `ensure_chrome` with `user_data_dir=None`, it creates a **fresh Chrome profile** each time (or uses the default one). This means any previous login state in the user's regular Chrome profile is NOT available.\n\nBut wait, looking more carefully - the script is using port 9222 with `ensure_chrome`. \n\nThe key question is whether `user_data_dir` is being set when Chrome launches on port 9222. The `ensure_chrome` function in the `chrome_launcher` module determines if a new data directory is created or an existing one is used. If it's creating a fresh profile each time, then the session that's supposed to restore cookies from the last login would be empty.\n\nLooking at the `_connect` function in `cli.py`, it only sets `user_data_dir` if the user explicitly passes `--account` via `_resolve_account()`. Since the cron job doesn't use `--account`, it defaults to `None`, which means `ensure_chrome` gets called without a user data directory argument. This could be the root cause—the profile state isn't being persisted between runs because no dedicated profile directory is specified. , or does it only apply when there's a `user_data_dir` argument? I need to trace through the `ensure_chrome` function to see how it handles the default case when no explicit user data directory is provided. Looking at the port configuration across the scripts, I see that `update_xhs_web_session.sh` hardcodes port 9222 without specifying a user data directory, while `cli.py` uses the same default port but conditionally applies one based on the account. This inconsistency might be the root cause—the session update script could be creating a fresh Chrome instance each time rather than reusing an authenticated profile. I'm tracing through the flow: `check-login` invokes `_connect` which calls `ensure_chrome` without a `user_data_dir`, then creates a fresh page via `get_or_create_page()` that navigates to the explore URL. The problem emerges because this new page lacks the login state from any pre-existing authenticated session, so when it tries to fetch the QR code, there's no logged-in context to work with. The issue is that when `check-login` opens a fresh page without a user data directory, it doesn't inherit any existing login sessions from the browser. But the `update_xhs_web_session.sh` script uses the same Chrome instance, so there might be a way to detect if the browser is already logged in through a different mechanism like cookie files rather than relying on the page state alone.\n\nLet me check the cron job configuration to understand when and how these scripts are actually triggered.","thinkingSignature":"7c8886242abb90925e8484a60fea8c571e5c7e9f12c90393b257a8b3635f76dd"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_klxci4yr2mcn_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/crontab_setup.txt"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":28291,"output":645,"cacheRead":24877,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53813,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773971193171}}
