{"type":"message","id":"d661569c","parentId":"ea4bcc54","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:47:26.033Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_jvxn798gn3tg_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Checklist: Heartbeat Quant Ops\n\n## 08:50 Morning News Push Check\n\n### State File\n```bash\ncat ~/.openclaw/workspace/memory/global_market_morning_0850_state.json\n```\n\n### Rules\n- [ ] 检查 `status` / `generated_at` / `last_success_at` / `last_failure_at`\n- [ ] 若交易日 08:50 之后仍无当日成功记录，主动汇报阻断原因\n- [ ] 若 `status` 为 `GENERATION_FAILED` 或 `PUSH_FAILED`，主动汇报错误摘要与日志路径\n- [ ] 若已成功且无新增变化，保持安静\n\n## Quant Research Mainline Health\n\n### Command\n```bash\ncd ~/.openclaw/workspace\npython3 scripts/run_investment_research_mainline_guard.py\n```\n\n### Output\n- `research/reports/investment_research_mainline_health_YYYYMMDD.md`\n- `research/reports/investment_research_mainline_health_YYYYMMDD.json`\n- 终端摘要：`🩺 量化投研主链巡检：OK/WARN/ALERT`\n\n### Rules\n- [ ] 检查退出码与 `overall_status`\n- [ ] `ALERT`：主动汇报晨报 / 稳定策略 / 回测队列是哪一项断裂\n- [ ] `WARN`：汇报缺口文件或未生成入口\n- [ ] `OK` 且无新增变化：保持安静\n\n## Trading-day Premarket Precheck (09:20-09:40)\n\n### Command\n```bash\ncd ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system\npython3 scripts/auto_run_premarket_precheck.py --available-cash 1000000 --account-nav 930000\n```\n\n### Rules\n- [ ] 无需用户提醒，交易日自动执行\n- [ ] 当日已执行过则跳过\n- [ ] 非交易日保持安静\n- [ ] 失败时主动汇报阻断原因与报告路径\n- [ ] 成功时汇报 `precheck` / `orders` / `brief` 路径\n\n## Daily Strategy Audit\n\n### Command\n```bash\ncd ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system\npython3 scripts/run_daily_strategy_audit.py\n```\n\n### Output\n- `research/reports/daily_strategy_audit_YYYYMMDD.md`\n- `research/reports/daily_strategy_audit_YYYYMMDD.json`\n\n### Rules\n- [ ] `PASS`：简要汇报核心指标与路径\n- [ ] `ALERT`：主动汇报未通过项与修复建议\n\n## Daily Enhancements\n\n### Command\n```bash\ncd ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system\npython3 scripts/run_daily_enhancements.py\n```\n\n### Output\n- `research/reports/sector_heatmap_latest.html`\n- `research/reports/sector_heatmap_summary.json`\n- `research/reports/daily_enhancement_YYYYMMDD.json`\n\n### Rules\n- [ ] 双源验证失败：主动告警\n- [ ] 热力图失败：主动告警\n- [ ] 正常运行：简要汇报上涨/下跌板块数\n\n## Live Dashboard + Feishu Push\n\n### Commands\n```bash\ncd ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system\npython3 scripts/sync_ths_app_data.py\npython3 scripts/sync_ths_exports.py\npython3 scripts/generate_live_global_dashboard.py\n```\n\n### Output\n- `research/reports/live_global_dashboard_latest.html`\n- `research/reports/live_global_dashboard_YYYYMMDD.html`\n\n### Push Rules\n- [ ] 成功后主动发飞书 DM：面板路径、precheck 状态、年化/回撤/夏普、买卖记录数、A股温度摘要\n- [ ] `needs_permission=true`：提示给 OpenClaw/终端 Full Disk Access\n- [ ] 导出为空：提示“同花顺暂无可用导出数据/账户为空”\n- [ ] 生成失败：主动发报错摘要与修复建议\n- [ ] 非交易时段不含“可执行买价”，只给预算/优先级/开盘触发条件\n- [ ] 当天已推送且无新增数据，可保持安静\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773971246023}}
{"type":"message","id":"2bb8866c","parentId":"d661569c","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:48:08.376Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see there's no xhs sync in the heartbeat. But the ACTIVE_TASK says \"9点同步任务\". Maybe it's not a cron job but an OpenClaw skill/session. Let me look for any scheduled task or OpenClaw cron related to xhs.\n\nActually, looking at the ACTIVE_TASK more carefully:\n\n\"Goal: 定位并修复小红书扫码登录页过快关闭的问题，保证用户有足够时间扫码并恢复 9 点同步任务\"\n\n\"Current: 排查 9 点同步任务触发的登录链路，定位扫码页为何会在短时间内被关闭或切走\"\n\nSo the issue is specifically about the login page closing too fast. \n\nI think I found the culprit in `cli.py`'s `cmd_check_login` function. When it retrieves the QR code and saves it to a file, it also opens that file automatically for display. The problem is likely that the login tab gets closed or the page navigates away before the user can complete the scan, since the code immediately displays the QR code and then proceeds with other operations that might interfere with the login flow. `, `cli.py` saves the login tab and clears the session tab, then outputs the result and exits in the `finally` block. But actually, the browser is closed too—`browser.close()` is called in the `finally` block of `cmd_check_login`. Wait, no. Let me look again:\n\n```python\ndef cmd_check_login(args: argparse.Namespace) -> None:\n    ...\n    browser, page = _connect(args)\n    try:\n        ...\n        _output(result, exit_code=1)\n    finally:\n        # 只断开 CDP 连接，不关闭 tab——保留登录页面\n        browser.close()\n```\n\nAfter `browser.close()`, the CDP WebSocket connection closes but the Chrome tab remains open with the login page still displayed. So `cmd_check_login` itself shouldn't be causing the login page to close.\n\nThe real issue might be with `update_xhs_web_session.sh`. This script launches Chrome, creates a new page, navigates to the explore URL, and waits for the page to load. The problem could be that `wait_dom_stable()` and the subsequent 2-second sleep aren't properly accounting for dynamic content loading, or the login page gets closed by some other mechanism in the session update flow. So the problem is that `new_page()` creates a fresh tab without any session data, and when it navigates to xiaohongshu.com/explore, the site requires login to access that content. The user probably has an existing logged-in session in their browser, but this new page doesn't inherit it. When the site detects no authenticated session, it redirects to the login page, which would explain why the QR code window appears briefly and then closes—the script might be triggering a login flow that gets interrupted or automatically dismissed. I'm realizing the session file approach has a fundamental flaw—if a previous command crashed, `_clear_session_tab` wouldn't have run, so the stale target_id would still be loaded and cause the connection to fail. The real issue might be that when multiple commands run in quick succession, they each try to use the same tab or create new ones, and something about the timing or the page state is causing the navigation to behave unexpectedly. The 120-second timeout in `wait_for_login` should give enough time for the user to scan the QR code, so the login page closing prematurely isn't due to that. I'm wondering if the real issue is that when the system is headless, it's automatically switching to a different login method rather than waiting for the QR code scan to complete. to headed mode or exits.\n\nActually, looking at `_qrcode_fallback`:\n\n```python\ndef _qrcode_fallback(browser, page, args: argparse.Namespace) -> None:\n    ...\n    browser.close()\n    result: dict = {\n        ...\n        \"message\": (\n            \"验证码发送受限，已切换为二维码登录，请扫码。\"\n            \"扫码后运行 wait-login 等待登录结果。\"\n        ),\n    }\n    ...\n    _output(result, exit_code=1)\n```\n\nThis DOES close the browser (`browser.close()`) AND exits with the JSON result. If the headless cron job calls `check-login`, and the system is headless, it would exit immediately after outputting the JSON.\n\nBut `_headless_fallback` is for the `publish` command when not logged in in headless mode. The `check-login` command uses `ensure_chrome(port=args.port, headless=not has_display())`. When `has_display()` is False, Chrome runs in headless mode with no GUI.\n\nSo when `check-login` runs from a cron job in a headless server environment, Chrome launches in headless mode and connects via CDP. The `fetch_qrcode` function checks if already logged in by looking for the login status element—if not found, it navigates to the explore page and retrieves the QR code for the login flow.\n\nThe `fetch_qrcode` call happens before `browser.close()`, so it shouldn't be the culprit. But I need to trace through the actual sequence: `_connect` creates a fresh page, `fetch_qrcode` navigates and waits for the QR code element with a 15-second timeout, then returns the image data. The issue might be that navigation itself is getting interrupted or the page is closing before the QR code is fully rendered.\n\nWait—`fetch_qrcode` uses `wait_for_element` which blocks until the element appears or times out after 15 seconds. If the login dialog doesn't show up within that window, the function fails. The real problem might be that小红书 has anti-bot measures that detect the headless Chrome and either withhold the QR code or redirect to a captcha page, causing `wait_for_element` to timeout and the whole flow to break.\n\nActually, looking back at the ACTIVE_TASK description about the QR code expiring too quickly—the user might not even be seeing the login dialog appear before it closes. Let me reconsider whether the issue is that Chrome is being restarted or closed prematurely, or if there's something about how the browser context is being managed that's causing the login state to reset.\n\nI should trace through how the cron job actually triggers this—if `check-login` is being called every day at 9am, it's probably creating a fresh browser context each time rather than reusing an authenticated session, which would explain why the user keeps getting pushed back to the login screen even after scanning the QR code successfully.\n\nThe real issue might be in `ensure_chrome` itself. If it's restarting Chrome when the port is already in use, that would kill any existing authenticated session and force the user to re-authenticate. I need to check how that function determines whether to start a new instance versus connecting to an existing one.","thinkingSignature":"f8cacdb06973d191a6793cd1719f9fcd0e0d0357b15653ddb251a2fa6d9f07d7"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_bg426c7v9evl_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/skills/xiaohongshu-skills -name \"chrome_launcher.py\" 2>/dev/null","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":31474,"output":1453,"cacheRead":24877,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":57804,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773971246033}}
