{"type":"message","id":"3f85db58","parentId":"c64e5966","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:48:11.075Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me read the chrome_launcher to understand how it manages Chrome instances.","thinkingSignature":"f4cc99e7fa09b9b4c150ceda745798a1d0561cf16aa8e755d568beb88adb07cf"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hhyu8t5c21wh_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/skills/xiaohongshu-skills/scripts/chrome_launcher.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":32967,"output":66,"cacheRead":24877,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":57910,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773971288425}}
{"type":"message","id":"cae4c835","parentId":"3f85db58","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:48:11.129Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hhyu8t5c21wh_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"\"\"Chrome 进程管理（跨平台），对应 Go browser/browser.go 的进程管理部分。\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport contextlib\nimport json\nimport logging\nimport os\nimport platform\nimport shutil\nimport socket\nimport subprocess\nimport sys\nimport time\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nfrom xhs.stealth import STEALTH_ARGS\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n# 默认远程调试端口\nDEFAULT_PORT = 9222\n\n# 全局进程追踪\n_chrome_process: subprocess.Popen | None = None\n\n# 各平台 Chrome 默认路径\n_CHROME_PATHS: dict[str, list[str]] = {\n    \"Darwin\": [\n        \"/Applications/Google Chrome.app/Contents/MacOS/Google Chrome\",\n        \"/Applications/Chromium.app/Contents/MacOS/Chromium\",\n        \"/Applications/Microsoft Edge.app/Contents/MacOS/Microsoft Edge\",\n        \"/Applications/Brave Browser.app/Contents/MacOS/Brave Browser\",\n    ],\n    \"Linux\": [\n        \"/usr/bin/google-chrome\",\n        \"/usr/bin/google-chrome-stable\",\n        \"/usr/bin/chromium\",\n        \"/usr/bin/chromium-browser\",\n        \"/snap/bin/chromium\",\n    ],\n    \"Windows\": [\n        r\"C:\\Program Files\\Google\\Chrome\\Application\\chrome.exe\",\n        r\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Google\\Chrome\\Application\\chrome.exe\",\n    ],\n}\n\n\ndef _get_default_data_dir() -> str:\n    \"\"\"返回默认 Chrome Profile 目录路径。\"\"\"\n    return str(Path.home() / \".xhs\" / \"chrome-profile\")\n\n\ndef is_port_open(port: int, host: str = \"127.0.0.1\") -> bool:\n    \"\"\"TCP socket 级端口检测（秒级响应）。\"\"\"\n    with socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM) as s:\n        s.settimeout(1)\n        try:\n            s.connect((host, port))\n            return True\n        except (ConnectionRefusedError, TimeoutError, OSError):\n            return False\n\n\ndef find_chrome() -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"查找 Chrome 可执行文件路径。\"\"\"\n    # 环境变量优先\n    env_path = os.getenv(\"CHROME_BIN\")\n    if env_path and os.path.isfile(env_path):\n        return env_path\n\n    # which/where 查找（含 Windows chrome.exe）\n    chrome = (\n        shutil.which(\"google-chrome\")\n        or shutil.which(\"chromium\")\n        or shutil.which(\"chrome\")\n        or shutil.which(\"chrome.exe\")\n    )\n    if chrome:\n        return chrome\n\n    # 平台默认路径\n    system = platform.system()\n\n    # Windows: 额外检查环境变量路径\n    if system == \"Windows\":\n        for env_var in (\"PROGRAMFILES\", \"PROGRAMFILES(X86)\", \"LOCALAPPDATA\"):\n            base = os.environ.get(env_var, \"\")\n            if base:\n                candidate = os.path.join(base, \"Google\", \"Chrome\", \"Application\", \"chrome.exe\")\n                if os.path.isfile(candidate):\n                    return candidate\n\n    for path in _CHROME_PATHS.get(system, []):\n        if os.path.isfile(path):\n            return path\n\n    return None\n\n\ndef is_chrome_running(port: int = DEFAULT_PORT) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"检查指定端口的 Chrome 是否在运行（TCP 级检测）。\"\"\"\n    return is_port_open(port)\n\n\ndef launch_chrome(\n    port: int = DEFAULT_PORT,\n    headless: bool = False,\n    user_data_dir: str | None = None,\n    chrome_bin: str | None = None,\n) -> subprocess.Popen | None:\n    \"\"\"启动 Chrome 进程（带远程调试端口）。\n\n    Args:\n        port: 远程调试端口。\n        headless: 是否无头模式。\n        user_data_dir: 用户数据目录（Profile 隔离），默认 ~/.xhs/chrome-profile。\n        chrome_bin: Chrome 可执行文件路径。\n\n    Returns:\n        Chrome 子进程，若已在运行则返回 None。\n\n    Raises:\n        FileNotFoundError: 未找到 Chrome。\n    \"\"\"\n    global _chrome_process\n\n    # 已在运行则跳过\n    if is_port_open(port):\n        logger.info(\"Chrome 已在运行 (port=%d)，跳过启动\", port)\n        return None\n\n    if not chrome_bin:\n        chrome_bin = find_chrome()\n    if not chrome_bin:\n        raise FileNotFoundError(\"未找到 Chrome，请设置 CHROME_BIN 环境变量或安装 Chrome\")\n\n    # 默认 user-data-dir\n    if not user_data_dir:\n        user_data_dir = _get_default_data_dir()\n\n    args = [\n        chrome_bin,\n        f\"--remote-debugging-port={port}\",\n        f\"--user-data-dir={user_data_dir}\",\n        *STEALTH_ARGS,\n    ]\n\n    if headless:\n        args.append(\"--headless=new\")\n\n    # 代理\n    proxy = os.getenv(\"XHS_PROXY\")\n    if proxy:\n        args.append(f\"--proxy-server={proxy}\")\n        logger.info(\"使用代理: %s\", _mask_proxy(proxy))\n\n    logger.info(\"启动 Chrome: port=%d, headless=%s, profile=%s\", port, headless, user_data_dir)\n    process = subprocess.Popen(\n        args,\n        stdout=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n        stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n    )\n    _chrome_process = process\n\n    # 等待 Chrome 准备就绪\n    _wait_for_chrome(port)\n    return process\n\n\ndef close_chrome(process: subprocess.Popen) -> None:\n    \"\"\"关闭 Chrome 进程。\"\"\"\n    if process.poll() is not None:\n        return\n\n    try:\n        process.terminate()\n        process.wait(timeout=5)\n    except (subprocess.TimeoutExpired, OSError):\n        process.kill()\n        process.wait(timeout=3)\n\n    logger.info(\"Chrome 进程已关闭\")\n\n\ndef kill_chrome(port: int = DEFAULT_PORT) -> None:\n    \"\"\"关闭指定端口的 Chrome 实例。\n\n    策略: CDP Browser.close → terminate 追踪进程 → 端口查找终止进程。\n\n    Args:\n        port: Chrome 调试端口。\n    \"\"\"\n    global _chrome_process\n\n    # 策略1: 通过 CDP 关闭\n    try:\n        import requests\n\n        resp = requests.get(f\"http://127.0.0.1:{port}/json/version\", timeout=2)\n        if resp.status_code == 200:\n            ws_url = resp.json().get(\"webSocketDebuggerUrl\")\n            if ws_url:\n                import websockets.sync.client\n\n                ws = websockets.sync.client.connect(ws_url)\n                ws.send(json.dumps({\"id\": 1, \"method\": \"Browser.close\"}))\n                ws.close()\n                logger.info(\"通过 CDP Browser.close 关闭 Chrome (port=%d)\", port)\n                time.sleep(1)\n    except Exception:\n        pass\n\n    # 策略2: terminate 追踪的子进程\n    if _chrome_process and _chrome_process.poll() is None:\n        try:\n            _chrome_process.terminate()\n            _chrome_process.wait(timeout=5)\n            logger.info(\"通过 terminate 关闭追踪的 Chrome 进程\")\n        except Exception:\n            with contextlib.suppress(Exception):\n                _chrome_process.kill()\n    _chrome_process = None\n\n    # 策略3: 通过端口查找并终止进程（跨平台）\n    if is_port_open(port):\n        pids = _find_pids_by_port(port)\n        if pids:\n            for pid in pids:\n                _kill_pid(pid)\n            logger.info(\"通过进程终止关闭 Chrome (port=%d)\", port)\n\n    # 等待端口释放（最多 5s）\n    deadline = time.monotonic() + 5\n    while time.monotonic() < deadline:\n        if not is_port_open(port):\n            return\n        time.sleep(0.5)\n\n    if is_port_open(port):\n        logger.warning(\"端口 %d 仍被占用，kill 可能未完全生效\", port)\n\n\ndef ensure_chrome(\n    port: int = DEFAULT_PORT,\n    headless: bool = False,\n    user_data_dir: str | None = None,\n    chrome_bin: str | None = None,\n) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"确保 Chrome 在指定端口可用（一站式入口）。\n\n    如果 Chrome 已在运行，直接返回 True。\n    否则尝试启动 Chrome 并等待端口就绪。\n\n    Args:\n        port: 远程调试端口。\n        headless: 是否无头模式（仅新启动时生效）。\n        user_data_dir: 用户数据目录。\n        chrome_bin: Chrome 可执行文件路径。\n\n    Returns:\n        True 表示 Chrome 可用，False 表示启动失败。\n    \"\"\"\n    if is_port_open(port):\n        return True\n\n    try:\n        launch_chrome(\n            port=port, headless=headless, user_data_dir=user_data_dir, chrome_bin=chrome_bin,\n        )\n        return is_port_open(port)\n    except FileNotFoundError as e:\n        logger.error(\"启动 Chrome 失败: %s\", e)\n        return False\n\n\ndef restart_chrome(\n    port: int = DEFAULT_PORT,\n    headless: bool = False,\n    user_data_dir: str | None = None,\n    chrome_bin: str | None = None,\n) -> subprocess.Popen | None:\n    \"\"\"重启 Chrome：关闭当前实例后以新模式重新启动。\n\n    Args:\n        port: 远程调试端口。\n        headless: 是否无头模式。\n        user_data_dir: 用户数据目录。\n        chrome_bin: Chrome 可执行文件路径。\n\n    Returns:\n        新的 Chrome 子进程，或 None。\n    \"\"\"\n    logger.info(\"重启 Chrome: port=%d, headless=%s\", port, headless)\n    kill_chrome(port)\n    time.sleep(1)\n    return launch_chrome(\n        port=port,\n        headless=headless,\n        user_data_dir=user_data_dir,\n        chrome_bin=chrome_bin,\n    )\n\n\ndef _wait_for_chrome(port: int, timeout: float = 15.0) -> None:\n    \"\"\"等待 Chrome 调试端口就绪（TCP 级检测）。\"\"\"\n    deadline = time.monotonic() + timeout\n    while time.monotonic() < deadline:\n        if is_port_open(port):\n            logger.info(\"Chrome 已就绪 (port=%d)\", port)\n            return\n        time.sleep(0.5)\n    logger.warning(\"等待 Chrome 就绪超时 (port=%d)\", port)\n\n\ndef _find_pids_by_port(port: int) -> list[int]:\n    \"\"\"查找占用指定端口的进程 PID（跨平台）。\"\"\"\n    try:\n        if sys.platform == \"win32\":\n            result = subprocess.run(\n                [\"netstat\", \"-ano\", \"-p\", \"TCP\"],\n                capture_output=True,\n                text=True,\n                timeout=5,\n            )\n            if result.returncode != 0:\n                return []\n            pids: list[int] = []\n            for line in result.stdout.splitlines():\n                if f\":{port}\" in line and \"LISTENING\" in line:\n                    parts = line.split()\n                    with contextlib.suppress(ValueError, IndexError):\n                        pids.append(int(parts[-1]))\n            return list(set(pids))\n        else:\n            result = subprocess.run(\n                [\"lsof\", \"-ti\", f\":{port}\"],\n                capture_output=True,\n                text=True,\n                timeout=5,\n            )\n            if result.returncode != 0 or not result.stdout.strip():\n                return []\n            pids = []\n            for p in result.stdout.strip().split(\"\\n\"):\n                with contextlib.suppress(ValueError):\n                    pids.append(int(p))\n            return pids\n    except Exception:\n        return []\n\n\ndef _kill_pid(pid: int) -> None:\n    \"\"\"终止指定 PID 的进程（跨平台）。\"\"\"\n    try:\n        if sys.platform == \"win32\":\n            subprocess.run(\n                [\"taskkill\", \"/PID\", str(pid), \"/F\"],\n                capture_output=True,\n                timeout=5,\n            )\n        else:\n            import signal\n\n            os.kill(pid, signal.SIGTERM)\n    except Exception:\n        logger.debug(\"终止进程 %d 失败\", pid)\n\n\ndef _mask_proxy(proxy_url: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"隐藏代理 URL 中的敏感信息。\"\"\"\n    from urllib.parse import urlparse\n\n    try:\n        parsed = urlparse(proxy_url)\n        if parsed.username:\n            return proxy_url.replace(parsed.username, \"***\").replace(parsed.password or \"\", \"***\")\n    except Exception:\n        pass\n    return proxy_url\n\n\ndef has_display() -> bool:\n    \"\"\"检测当前环境是否有图形界面（用于自动选择登录方式）。\"\"\"\n    system = platform.system()\n    if system in (\"Windows\", \"Darwin\"):\n        return True  # Windows / macOS 默认有 GUI\n    # Linux: 检查 DISPLAY 或 WAYLAND_DISPLAY 环境变量\n    return bool(os.getenv(\"DISPLAY\") or os.getenv(\"WAYLAND_DISPLAY\"))\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773971291113}}
{"type":"message","id":"a6cb3d47","parentId":"cae4c835","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:50:03.033Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. Let me trace the issue:\n\n1. **`update_xhs_web_session.sh`**:\n   - Sets `CHROME_BIN` to Microsoft Edge (not Chrome!)\n   - Calls `ensure_chrome(port=9222, headless=False)` without `user_data_dir`\n   - `ensure_chrome` → `launch_chrome` → sets `user_data_dir = _get_default_data_dir()` = `~/.xhs/chrome-profile`\n   - Creates a new page and navigates to xiaohongshu.com/explore\n   - The page has NO logged-in session because it's using the default `~/.xhs/chrome-profile` directory, which may or may not have the user's cookies\n\n2. **The core problem**:\n   - When `ensure_chrome(port=9222)` is called, it checks if the port is already open\n   - If Chrome/Edge is already running on 9222 (from a previous session), it skips launching a new instance\n   - BUT if the user was logged in through their normal browser (not the CLI's Chrome instance), the CLI won't see that session\n   - The CLI uses `~/.xhs/chrome-profile` as the default data directory, so if the user logged in through a different Chrome profile, the CLI won't have access to those credentials\n   - This means each invocation creates a fresh profile, and any previous login state gets lost\n\n3. **Why the QR code page closes quickly**:\n   - The `cmd_check_login` command calls `browser.close()` which only closes the CDP connection but leaves the Chrome tab open\n   - However, the QR code might expire quickly or the page structure changes, causing the scan to fail before completion\n\nThe real problem is likely that Chrome is being relaunched without the `--user-data-dir` pointing to where the session actually exists, so the login state isn't persisted between runs.\n\nIf the user's normal browser has XHS cookies stored in their regular profile, but the CLI is using a fresh temporary profile each time, then the session appears logged in the browser but not through the CLI. The solution would be to either point the CLI to the user's actual Chrome profile directory, or ensure the same profile is reused consistently so cookies persist. So the session file stores the target ID of the last created page, which gets reused in subsequent commands through `_load_session_tab`. The issue might be that when the session expires or the page gets closed, the next command falls back to creating a new page that doesn't have the login state. I should check the `_connect_saved_tab` function to see how it handles reconnection when a saved tab becomes unavailable.\n\nThe function tries to load the login tab ID, and if that page no longer exists, it logs a warning and falls back to getting an existing page instead of the saved one. This fallback behavior could be creating a new page without the necessary context.\n\nThe real question is what happens to that saved tab—the user might be closing it manually, or it could be getting garbage collected. But based on the script flow, when `check-login` calls `_save_login_tab`, it's storing the tab ID for later retrieval by `wait-login`. So if the user scans the QR code but the tab closes before `wait-login` runs, the function would fail to find the original tab and would need to handle that gracefully. The `_load_session_tab` is only called in `_connect`, not in `cmd_check_login` directly. Let me trace through the actual flow more carefully.\n\nWhen the skill runs `check-login`, it calls `_connect` which tries to load a saved session tab. If that tab has a `target_id`, it attempts to use it. But when `get_qrcode` is called separately, it goes through `_connect_saved_tab` instead and might fall back to a fresh page if the saved one isn't available.\n\nThe problem is that if a previous command crashed or the tab was reused elsewhere, the saved session tab might be stale, causing `_connect` to create yet another new page instead of reconnecting to the existing one. This means multiple browser contexts could pile up, and the QR code ends up in a different tab than where the user expects it. The issue might be that when Chrome connects but the specific tab has closed, `_connect` creates a new page and navigates to the explore URL, which doesn't have the QR code yet. The `wait_for_element` with a 15-second timeout would then fail if the QR code doesn't appear, but that wouldn't explain why the page closes prematurely—something else must be causing the premature closure.\n\nActually, I think the real culprit is a race condition between commands. When `check-login` saves the tab ID and closes the browser connection, a subsequent command like `wait-login` might try to use that same tab ID before it becomes invalid, or the system might be creating a duplicate tab that confuses the state. The QR code URL might also be getting invalidated after the image is generated—perhaps 小红书 ties the QR to a specific tab session rather than keeping it valid across reconnections. Looking at `_decode_qr_content`, I notice it sends the PNG bytes to an external API for decoding, which could introduce timing issues if the QR expires before the login attempt completes. I'm wondering if there's a timing issue with how the browser context is being managed. When `new_page()` creates a fresh tab and `wait_dom_stable()` pauses for 2 seconds, maybe the navigation hasn't fully settled before the QR code appears, causing the connection to drop prematurely. Or perhaps the cron job is running with different browser arguments than when the user manually logged in, which could explain why the session closes unexpectedly. Looking at the sequence of events, I think the core problem is that `check-login` creates a new Chrome tab with no prior session data, and when it navigates to xiaohongshu.com, the site detects no authentication and redirects to a login page—likely showing a QR code that expires quickly due to server-side timing constraints. The reason it closes so fast is probably because each time `check-login` runs (whether manually or via cron), it creates a fresh page that immediately navigates to xiaohongshu.com, which prompts for login again, and this cycle repeats.\n\nBut actually, the user reports it \"过快关闭,\" which sounds more like a UI automation issue rather than the login flow restarting. Maybe the page is closing because something in the script is calling `browser.close_page(page)` instead of just closing the CDP connection, or there's an error in the try-finally block that causes the tab to shut down prematurely.\n\nLet me reconsider: the QR code page should stay open since we're only closing the CDP connection, but what if Chrome itself is crashing? That could happen if the Chrome binary path is wrong—`update_xhs_web_session.sh` sets it to Microsoft Edge's location, but the actual Chrome browser on the system might be different. Or maybe the headless mode isn't working properly on this Mac, causing Chrome to close unexpectedly. I'm wondering if there's a timing issue between when the page is created and when the navigation happens—if `new_page()` creates a blank tab and then we immediately navigate, maybe the QR code doesn't have time to load properly before we try to read it. Or possibly the `wait_for_load()` and `wait_dom_stable()` calls are interfering with the QR code rendering itself.\n\nActually, the most likely culprit is that小红书 detects the headless Chrome browser and either withholds the QR code entirely or shows a captcha instead. Since the cron job runs Chrome in headed mode, it would display the browser window briefly, but if there's no QR code to show, the window might close or the process exits immediately without giving the user time to interact with anything.\n\nThe real issue is probably that when `update_xhs_web_session.sh` runs, it creates a new Chrome instance with a fresh profile that doesn't have the user's XHS cookies. So when it navigates to xiaohongshu.com, the site sees an unauthenticated session and either shows a login page with a QR code that expires immediately, or shows nothing at all because of bot detection. The user needs to log in first, but the QR code disappears too quickly for them to scan it. The simplest fix would be to reuse an existing Chrome profile that already has XHS cookies, or check if the user is already logged in via cookies before attempting the login flow.\n\nActually, I think the real problem is that both scripts are stepping on each other—`update_xhs_web_session.sh` creates one Chrome tab, then `check-login` creates another with different settings, and when `get-qrcode` tries to use the saved tab from `check-login`, the session might be stale or the tab might have been closed. The QR code itself could be fine, but the login detection is failing because the browser context is inconsistent across these different tool invocations. So the current Chrome instance has a tab open from the previous command, but the QR code page has already navigated away. When `_connect` tries to use that stale tab ID, it might fail silently or point to the wrong page. Meanwhile, `_connect_saved_tab` is checking the login tab file separately, but I'm not sure if these two mechanisms are actually coordinating properly or if there's a race condition where one command clears what the other needs. The stale tab ID gets reused across commands, creating duplicate tabs and fragmenting the browser state. This could cause issues if the original QR code tab is no longer accessible. Let me focus on the actual problems: the QR code expires too quickly on the server side, the CLI opens a fresh profile instead of reusing the authenticated session, and multiple tabs pile up when session management breaks down.\n\nFor the fixes, I could try increasing the QR code validity window or automatically refreshing it, pointing the Chrome profile to the user's actual browser data to preserve the login state, and improving tab reuse so new pages don't keep spawning unnecessarily.\n\nBut wait—I'm noticing the SKILL.md explicitly forbids using MCP tools and Go commands, yet the code is clearly using Python CDP to interact with Chrome. Let me look more carefully at what's actually happening here.\n\nThe real issue is that the 9am sync task seems to trigger a login flow that causes the QR code page to close prematurely. I should check whether the cron job or scheduled task is calling the login command in a way that's interfering with the browser session.\n\nLooking at the script flow, when `update_xhs_web_session.sh` navigates to the explore page and tries to get cookies, if the user isn't logged in, the browser would redirect to a login page instead. That would explain why the page appears to close—the navigation fails and the script exits before the user can complete the QR scan.\n\nThe issue is that this script doesn't implement a proper wait for login like `check-login` does. It just extracts cookies directly and exits, so if authentication is needed, the session cookie won't be found and the process fails silently.\n\nNow I'm realizing the core problem: both scripts are competing for the same Chrome profile and port 9222. If one script's browser instance closes, it could interfere with the other's tab. And more fundamentally, the `update_xhs_web_session.sh` script has no login waiting mechanism at all—it tries to grab cookies immediately after navigation, which won't work if the user isn't already logged in.\n\nThe real question is whether the user is expecting to see a login dialog during the 9am sync, or if the issue is that some other scheduled task like `morning_scan.py` is actually triggering the login flow and closing the window before the user can complete it. to handle the login flow. The QR code appears but then the login tab gets closed before the user can scan it, which suggests the issue might be with how the browser context is being managed when `wait-login` runs.\n\nIf a previous command left the browser in an inconsistent state—maybe it created a new page that doesn't have the QR code anymore—and then `wait-login` tries to connect to that stale page, it would fail to find the login status indicator and exit immediately, making it seem like the QR code page closed on its own.\n\nThe most likely culprit is that a cron job like `morning_scan.py` is running Chrome and navigating to the explore page, which either navigates away from the QR code tab or closes it entirely. But that script doesn't actually use Chrome, so it must be something else triggering the browser launch.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the real issue might be with how Chrome handles the `--user-data-dir` flag. If Chrome is already running with a user data directory and a script tries to launch it again with the same directory, it either reuses the existing instance or fails outright. If the user has XHS cookies in their regular browser profile but the script is trying to use a different or default data directory, the session won't be found and the login page appears instead. Plus, the `update_xhs_web_session.sh` script points to Microsoft Edge as the Chrome binary, which could cause compatibility issues.\n\nThe solution is probably to check whether the user is already logged in before launching Chrome, and if not, wait for them to complete the login flow. But the \"过快关闭\" problem is specifically about the QR code page closing too quickly. The `wait-login` command polls for the login status every 0.3 seconds, so if the tab doesn't have the login status element, it just keeps waiting. The issue might be that the QR code page itself is unstable or closing before the user can scan it.\n\nI'm thinking the QR code might be tied to a specific CDP session—if the connection drops or the page crashes, the QR becomes invalid immediately. Or there could be multiple Chrome instances competing for the same port, which would cause instability. The root cause is likely that when the QR code tab navigates away or closes, the user loses their chance to scan. Since the scripts don't actually wait for login, they just exit after navigating to the page, the QR code page would close almost instantly when the script finishes. I need to focus on the concrete findings from my analysis. The scripts like `update_xhs_web_session.sh` and `cmd_check_login` navigate to xiaohongshu.com and create fresh browser tabs with no authentication, which would display a login QR code. But if these scripts run as cron jobs and exit quickly, the user wouldn't see the QR code page long enough to scan it. Looking at `cmd_check_login` specifically, it calls `_output` to print the JSON result before the `finally` block closes the browser connection, so the script terminates right after outputting the result. The `finally` block runs after `_output` prints the JSON result, so `browser.close()` executes before the process exits—but that shouldn't cause the page to close since the CDP connection closing doesn't terminate the actual Chrome tab. The issue might be that the headless cron job runs when the user isn't actively using their computer, so they never see the QR code in the first place. When they do encounter the login page later, it could be stale or closed. But the user specifically said \"扫码登录页过快关闭,\" which suggests they did see it but it closed before they could scan. Let me reconsider whether Chrome itself is crashing or being killed, or if the page is actually closing for a different reason.\n\nLooking at the SKILL.md instructions, the workflow should be: first call `check-login` to display the QR code and get the URL, then tell the user to scan it, then call `wait-login` to wait for the scan to complete. But the user might be skipping the `wait-login` step entirely, which would explain why the page appears to close—the script finishes after displaying the QR code and never actually waits for authentication to finish.\n\nThe real problem is that the QR code displayed in the chat is just an image—it's not connected to the actual browser tab where the user needs to complete the login. When the user scans the QR code on their phone, it needs to authenticate against the same browser session that's running the script. If the script doesn't properly maintain that connection or if the QR code expires before the user scans it, the whole flow breaks down.\n\nThe core issue seems to be that the login process isn't being properly maintained between when the QR code is shown and when the user completes the scan. Either the page is closing prematurely, or the authentication state isn't being preserved in a way that allows the `wait-login` command to detect when scanning is successful. The QR code in the chat image and the browser tab are separate entities—they share the same underlying data, but closing the CDP connection shouldn't affect the browser tab itself. However, if Chrome crashes or is killed externally, both would disappear, which could explain why the page closes. The \"过快关闭\" phrasing suggests the user is seeing the browser window disappear quickly, which points to either Chrome crashing from memory issues or resource constraints, or the browser being killed by the system when the script exits.\n\nLooking at the process flow more carefully: when `ensure_chrome` is called with default parameters, it uses a default user data directory that might be shared across different Chrome instances, causing conflicts. Or perhaps the system is running out of resources and killing the Chrome process. But I should reconsider whether the script itself is actually running in the background and completing normally.\n\nThe most likely scenario is that when the user says the page \"closes too fast,\" they're referring to the chat window where the QR code appears—this disappears as soon as the script finishes. The actual browser window might remain open, but the user is looking at the QR code in the chat and doesn't realize they need to interact with the browser itself. The script's QR code display and browser window are separate; the chat QR is just an image that vanishes when the process ends, while the browser tab persists. So the fix needs to ensure the QR code stays valid and the login page remains accessible in the browser long enough for the user to complete authentication. The login tab itself could be closing due to Chrome crashes, navigation events, or conflicting commands running simultaneously. But actually, I think I'm overcomplicating this—maybe the user's real issue is that the QR code just expires too quickly. Let me reconsider the core problem statement.\n\nLooking at how the QR code is generated and displayed, I see it's created once in `fetch_qrcode` by extracting the base64 image data from the page, then saved to a file and displayed to the user. The URL is only generated once as a fallback. If the user takes longer than the typical 60-second expiry time to scan, they'd need a fresh code, but the script would just keep showing them the expired one.\n\nThe real issue is that the script generates a QR code and immediately exits, leaving the browser tab open but unmanaged. If the tab gets closed—either by the user, another process, or Chrome itself—the session is lost. I think the safest approach is to address this by having the script wait for login properly rather than exiting immediately, and potentially save the tab ID so it can be reconnected if the session breaks.\n\nActually, rereading the original problem, the core issue is that the user needs enough time to scan the QR code and complete the login flow. So the solution should ensure the login page stays open and valid, the QR code doesn't expire before they can scan it, and the system waits for the login to actually succeed before moving forward.","thinkingSignature":"67494343dd622a648f7ca56182876d4d797d7a35bd89ca8eb419f9e6cc17b449"},{"type":"text","text":"Now let me look at the core issue more carefully - how the 9am task interacts with login:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"c