{"type":"message","id":"c97599cf","parentId":"1ffc7a96","timestamp":"2026-03-20T01:55:46.281Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found the issue! The last row is `20260319` (March 19, 2026), and the `pct_change` is `-2.3141%`. But today is March 20, 2026 (a trading day). The data is from yesterday (March 19), not from today (March 20). So when the script calculates today's return, it's using yesterday's change as if it were today's.\n\nWait, let me re-read the function. `latest_index_return_pct` just reads the last row of the CSV and computes `pct_change()`. So:\n- Row before last (20260318): close = 8096.5948\n\n\n- Last row (20260319): close = 7909.2343\n- pct_change = (7909.2343 / 8096.5948 - 1) * 100 ≈ -2.31%\n\nThat's yesterday's return, but the gate is using it as if it's today's return. The real problem is that the CSV only extends through March 19, so when `latest_index_return_pct()` pulls the last row on March 20, it's still grabbing yesterday's data instead of today's. Either today's index data hasn't been written to the CSV yet, or the function is computing the wrong date's return.\n\nSince today is Friday and we're between market closes, yesterday's -2.31% return is being treated as the current market condition. The gate logic assumes it has today's data when it actually only has yesterday's, so it's incorrectly flagging a market halt based on stale information. I need to verify what the actual market data shows for today.","thinkingSignature":"3afdcb3c5dc7cfed16f5592fa0d717199fc07bd4d43a1c7b573c8673fb210abd"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xgyqla3aaqsr_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"tail -3 /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/daily_stock_analysis/index_000852_SH.csv && echo \"---\" && tail -3 /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/daily_stock_analysis/index_000300_SH.csv","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input"