pen price as the baseline since daily bars don't get updated until market close. Rather than modifying the existing CSV, I'll create a separate file to store the current prices after market opens.\n\nThe approach is to update `morning_scan.py` to fetch real-time index data after the market opens, store those prices, then have `latest_index_return_pct()` check the last update time against the current time to determine whether to use cached prices or fall back to the CSV data.\n\nBut there's a problem: if the date validation was returning 0.0 for stale data, how did we get -2.31% in the report? The CSV only has yesterday's data (03-19), so the date should have failed the check and returned 0.0 instead.\n\nWait, I need to trace through the execution order more carefully. The morning scan ran first at 09:00, then the precheck ran at 09:20 and would have hit the stale data warning. But the event watch report showing -2.31% was generated at 09:45, which means it must have read from a different data source than what the precheck was using.\n\nActually, looking at the timestamp on the CSV file (03-19 18:10), that's when it was last modified. So the issue is that the date validation in `latest_index_return_pct()` is checking if the last trade date (03-19) is before today (03-20), which should have triggered the warning and returned 0.0. But instead, the event watch report got -2.31%, which suggests either the validation wasn't actually running or the fix I thought I applied wasn't in place when the event watch script executed.\n\nLet me trace through the actual execution paths to see which script is actually pulling the data and where the date validation might be failing.","thinkingSignature":"fc3656a3ced748357c2f24bf4faeb23dd59e2ca16c44f52246dfda3e3e724a7b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qhjjvk7qnl9f_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport sys\nsys.path.insert(0, '/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system