{"type":"message","id":"0efcbbbf","parentId":"74fc7c83","timestamp":"2026-03-20T04:33:53.531Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see. The issue is:\n1. When `intraday_gate.enabled == False` (non-trading hours), the entire block starting at line 75 is skipped\n2. `intraday_runtime` stays as `base_runtime` (which has `mode: normal`)\n3. But `runtime_metrics.market_breadth` is a separate field that contains the pre-market breadth (which is 0.092 - way below threshold)\n4. The `base_runtime` was built using this breadth, but when it's below threshold, `halt` should have been set\n\nWait, let me re-check the base_runtime. Actually, the issue is that the `event_watch` halt reason says \"market_breadth(0.0920) <= 0.2800\". But `runtime_risk_state` shows `market_breadth: 0.377` in runtime_metrics. \n\nSo the real problem is that `runtime_metrics.market_breadth` (0.377) and `event_watch.current.market_breadth` (0.092) are showing different values, which suggests the breadth computation happened at different times or using different data sources. Let me trace through what the tester is actually comparing.","thinkingSignature":"c9d1c616c2dd816b34e77d5eb3d44c28c3a348144ddff545c53f29a60dd6ac3c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_e6n7dilqbfaq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\new = json.load(open('/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/research/reports/investment_research_event_watch_20260320.json'))\nrt = json.load(open('/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/runtime_risk_state_latest.json'))\n\nprint('=== event_watch ===')\nprint('paper_execution_status.mode:', ew.get('current', {}).get('paper_execution_status', {}).get('mode'))\nprint('paper_execution_status.halt_reason:', ew.get('current', {}).get('paper_execution_status', {}).get('halt_reason'))\nprint()\nprint('=== runtime_risk_state ===')\nprint('latest_runtime.mode:', rt.get('latest_runtime', {