{"type":"message","id":"99a1bf04","parentId":"3e2db398","timestamp":"2026-03-20T04:36:05.771Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the `paper_execution_summary` shows `market_breadth = 0.092`. This means `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` used `runtime_metrics.market_breadth = 0.092` when building the execution status. But `runtime_risk_state_latest` shows `runtime_metrics.market_breadth = 0.377`.\n\nThis means there are TWO different `runtime_risk_state` files - one used by `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` (which produced `market_breadth = 0.092`) and one that we checked (`runtime_risk_state_latest.json` which shows `market_breadth = 0.377`).\n\n\nThe issue is that `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` runs during the morning precheck and pulls from `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` at that time, which had `market_breadth = 0.092`. Later when I checked the same file, it showed `0.377` because `run_intraday_risk_recheck.py` ran again and overwrote it. The morning reading was stale data before our fixes.","thinkingSignature":"2cd1c241eafad61258d262dfe02157532c67070317c0d964e87e1f058bac9b05"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_s91g2r0px36m_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\n# Check the intraday recheck dated file\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport glob\nfiles = sorted(glob.glob('/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/intraday_risk_recheck_20260320*.json'))\nprint('Intraday recheck files:', [f.split('/')[-1] for f in files])\nfor f in files:\n    d = json.load(open(f))\n    print(f.split('/')[-1])\n    print('  runtime_metrics.market_breadth:', d.get('runtime_metrics', {}).get('market_breadth'))\n    print('  latest_runtime.mode:', d.get('latest_runtime', {}).get('mode'))\n\" 2>&1","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":91057,"output":433,"cacheRead":24877,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":11