unning against an older version of the runtime_risk_state file before the 14:20 update, or there's something different about how it's reading the file compared to my test. I'm wondering if the issue is that `latest_runtime` exists but is empty when the conditional check runs, even though accessing it directly shows the correct data. The only way `latest_runtime` could be falsy is if it's an empty dict `{}`, which would make the `or` fallback to `report_runtime` instead of using the actual runtime state.","thinkingSignature":"c729e1d4a7eda9aa5361da54056635c2262180c02593db80d389dd38a3e103c3"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_718kbn4c5zsg_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace && python3 -c \"\nimport json\nimport sys\nsys.path.insert(0, 'scripts')\nfrom run_investment_research_event_watch import apply_runtime_overlay, load_runtime_overlay\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\ndate_tag = datetime.now().strftime('%Y%m%d')\nprint('date_tag:', date_tag)\n\nruntime_obj, report_obj = load_runtime_overlay(date_tag)\nprint('runtime_obj.date_tag:', runtime_obj.get('date_tag'))\nprint('runtime_obj.latest_runtime is empty:', bool(runtime_obj.get('latest_runtime')))\nprint('runtime_obj.latest_runtime.mode:', runtime_obj.get('latest_runtime', {}).get('mode'))\nprint('str(runtime_obj.date_tag) == date_tag:', str(runtime_obj.get('date_tag') or '') == date_tag)\nprint('bool(latest_runtime):', bool(runtime_obj.get('latest_runtime') or {}))\n\" 2>&1","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":99506,"output":743,"cacheRead":24756,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125005,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773988327813}}
