{"type":"message","id":"acda8d75","parentId":"e03d477f","timestamp":"2026-03-20T07:24:57.272Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see clearly:\n\nOn 20260319:\n- ALL intraday rechecks showed `mode=halt` and `halt=True` throughout the entire trading day\n- Even at 10:06, 11:00, 13:30, 14:20 - all showed `halt=True`\n- market_breadth was 0.649 (this is actually a high breadth value, not low)\n\nSo the halt was triggered NOT by market breadth, but by something else - likely the `index_ret_pct` being -2.31% (from the old data bug we fixed today). \n\nAh, so the -2.31% figure from the CSV was causing the halt to trigger, even though the actual market breadth was 0.649 which should have overridden it. The `allow_new_buy_when_riskoff` setting in the risk config is probably what forced the halt despite the high breadth reading.\n\nLooking at the execution data though, the buys for 002151 and 002173 actually went through with a risk_status of \"normal\" - which shouldn't have happened if halt was truly active. Either the intraday risk recheck wasn't running during the morning window when these signals were generated, or there's a separate morning precheck that's bypassing the halt logic that I need to trace through the prepare_paper_orders flow.","thinkingSignature":"f6a8e31ee19e0fd81ff0bdb2f8d520f08d39e1de5c87c4763d3c837a5a8610f0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_p8zh3lbtuwfe_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"runtime_metrics\\|runtime_risk_state\\|halt_new_buy\\|market_breadth\" /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/prepare_paper_orders_v1.py 2>/dev/null | head -30","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":99115,"output":368,"cacheRead":24877,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":124360,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":177399